s is because numpy computes the entire row at once. In the TypeScript, we could add early termination (if the minimum value in the current row exceeds maxDistance, we can return False early), but the task says not to improve the algorithm. So the current implementation is correct.\n\nActually, let me re-read the TypeScript code one more time to make sure there are no bugs:\n\n```typescript\nexport function levenshteinB(\n  str1: string,\n  str2: string,\n  maxDistance: number,\n  caseInsensitive: boolean = false,\n): boolean {\n  let source = str1.trim();\n  let target = str2.trim();\n  if (!source || !target || source.length === 0 || target.length === 0) {\n    return false;\n  }\n  if (maxDistance >= source.length || maxDistance >= target.length) {\n    return false;\n  }\n  if (caseInsensitive) {\n    source = source.toLowerCase();\n    target = target.toLowerCase();\n  }\n  if (source.length < target.length) {\n    return levenshteinB(target, source, maxDistance, caseInsensitive);\n  }\n  const previousRow: number[] = [];\n  for (let i = 0; i <= target.length; i++) {\n    previousRow.push(i);\n  }\n\n  for (const s of source) {\n    const currentRow: number[] = [previousRow[0] + 1];\n    for (let j = 1; j <= target.length; j++) {\n      const subCost = previousRow[j - 1] + (target[j - 1] !== s ? 1 : 0);\n      const insertCost = previousRow[j] + 1;\n      const delCost = currentRow[j - 1] + 1;\n      currentRow[j] = Math.min(subCost, insertCost, delCost);\n    }\n    for (let i = 0; i < previousRow.length; i++) {\n      previousRow[i] = currentRow[i];\n    }\n  }\n\n  return previousRow[target.length] <= maxDistance;\n}\n```\n\nI notice that `previousRow` is initialized with `push(i)` for i from 0 to target.length. This gives [0, 1, 2, ..., target.length]. This is correct — it represents the base case dp[0][j] = j.\n\nThe inner loop computes currentRow[j] for j from 1 to target.length. currentRow[0] = previousRow[0] + 1 = i + 1 (1-indexed source character). Wait